Azure VNets allow resources to communicate with the internet using public IP addresses, load balancers, or application gateways.

Resources can either have direct internet access or be exposed through controlled endpoints.

For example, a web server in a VNet can be assigned a public IP to serve users globally.

A real-life use case is hosting a website accessible to users worldwide.

Another example is restricting internet access for backend systems while allowing frontend services to communicate externally.

Internet communication must be carefully managed to ensure security.
